-003.jpg","typeData":{"source":"PR","altText":"Dacia Sandero","height":"84","credit":"PR","caption":"Dacia Sandero: the Romanian motoring company is now owned by Renault.","width":"140"}}]}]},{"webTitle":"Volkswagen XL1: car review | Martin Love","webPublicationDate":"2013-09-15T09:38:00Z","sectionName":"Technology","sectionId":"technology","id":"technology/2013/sep/15/volkswagen-golf-xl1-car-review","fields":{"secureThumbnail":"https://static-secure.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Observer/Pix/pictures/2013/9/11/1378913494483/The-Volkswagen-XL1-003.jpg","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/3tkzd","standfirst":"The XL1 does 313 miles to the gallon.  But the technology in VW's showstopper is coming to a Golf near you soon","hasStoryPackage":"true","lastModified":"2014-01-09T14:31:05Z","body":"<p><strong>Price</strong> £95,000 <br /><strong>MPG</strong> 313<br /><strong>Top speed </strong>99mph<br /><br />A supercar on the streets of Chelsea barely gets a second look these days, but the two young men in front of us in red jeans, sockless loafers and surprisingly tight Hawaiian shirts are standing slack jawed on the pavement. \"Hugo, what the hell is that?\" one bellows at the other. Hugo has no idea and sticks his  head in the window. \"What's this, buddy?\" he asks of Peter Wouda,  one of VW's brightest talents, who is over from the firm's design HQ in Potsdam to show off his new baby. \"It's the <a href=\"http://www.volkswagen.co.uk/new/xl1?gclid=CL3Atda-kbkCFS3HtAodNWAAUg\" title=\"\">XL1</a>,\" Peter replies in flawless English. Hugo looks impressed and then asks what it runs on, pushing his floppy fringe off his face. But before Peter can reply he guffaws: \"Cham-bloody-pagne!\"</p><p>We are driving the world's cleanest and most fuel-efficient production car. It's a miracle of super-lightweight performance engineering. Its diesel-electric hybrid engines give it a fuel consumption of 313 miles per gallon – that's 10 times the figure an average car achieves. While hitting this astronomical target it emits a piffling 21g of carbon per km. Ironically, that is the same amount generated by a cyclist.</p><p>The ultra-frugal XL1 looks like a&nbsp;vision of the future, but it is already in limited production. So far 50 have been manufactured in Volkswagen's Osnabrück factory (which also produces the Golf Cabriolet and the Porsche Boxster) and there are immediate plans to make 200, though that could soon rise to 5,000. Peter explains: \"They will be made to be sold and driven – they are not for collectors. But the XL1 is mostly about technology that will make its way down into our regular cars.\"</p><p>The body is made of carbon-fibre reinforced polymer and is created from a single monocoque mould. This one-piece construction, a&nbsp;sort of exoskeleton, makes the car stronger and lighter as it supports loads through its skin – like a table-tennis ball. The drivetrain melds a two-cylinder 800cc diesel with a tiny electric motor.</p><p>The twin forces which shaped this car are weight and aerodynamics. Everything possible has been done to optimise these two. It doesn't have electric windows, for instance, as hand winders weigh less. There are no wing mirrors as these create drag. Instead, tiny rear-facing cameras transmit an image on to a screen on the door panels. The car has fared-in wheels, skinny tyres and an entirely flat bottom. The extreme tear-drop shape makes it incredibly \"slippery\". If the tail had been followed to a tapered tip it would have been 7m long – a perfect sperm-like shape, agrees Peter. The entire car, including two engines, crash protection, sat nav, radio, etc, weighs in at less than 800kg. That's featherweight.</p><p>Inside, the XL1 looks remarkably normal. The car is so radical and challenging that Peter and his team wanted the interior to be familiar, calm and uncluttered. Much of the kit is the same as you'd find in a Golf.</p><p>To drive it doesn't feel alien or peculiar. It zips along, it's easy to manoeuvre, it's fun. When the diesel kicks in it barks like a&nbsp;\"little terrier in the boot\". It sounds odd to say this, but this most ultramodern, dynamic, game-changing, avant-garde, frugal Dougal of a vehicle – a&nbsp;time traveller into the future of motoring – feels instantly familiar and congenial.  And, somehow, that is very comforting. Champagne all round!</p><p></p><p><br /><a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=a3Z9kuCvRDc&amp;feature=youtu.be\" title=\"\">Reading this on mobile? See the video of the XL1 driving through London here</a></p><p></p><p><br />Email Martin at <a href=\"mailto:martin.love@observer.co.uk\" title=\"\">martin.love@observer.co.uk</a>. Follow Martin on Twitter <a href=\"https://twitter.com/martinlove166\" title=\"\">@MartinLove166</a></p>","headline":"Volkswagen XL1: car review","trailText":"The XL1 does 313 miles to the gallon.  But the technology in VW's showstopper is coming to a Golf near you soon, says <strong>Martin Love</strong>","newspaperPageNumber":"63","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"The Observer","showInRelatedContent":"true","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Observer/Pix/pictures/2013/9/11/1378913494483/The-Volkswagen-XL1-003.jpg","wordcount":"577","commentable":"false","internalContentCode":"417055219","allowUgc":"false","internalOctopusCode":"7983463","isPremoderated":"false","byline":"Martin Love","newspaperEditionDate":"2013-09-15T00:00:00Z","internalPageCode":"1963858","productionOffice":"UK","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2013-09-18T09:38:00Z"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/technology/2013/sep/15/volkswagen-golf-xl1-car-review","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/technology/2013/sep/15/volkswagen-golf-xl1-car-review","tags":[{"id":"technology/series/wheels","webTitle":"Wheels","description":"Martin Love covers new models, developments in the motoring industry and quirky tales from the highways and byways of the world of transport","type":"series","sectionId":"technology","